# Microbiota that reside on the skin  

Skin flora, commonly referred to as the **skin microbiota**, constitutes a intricate assemblage of microscopic organisms that colonize the surface of the human integumentary system. This community, often designated as the **cutaneous microbiota**, comprises numerous species that have adapted to the unique physicochemical environment of the epidermis and its appendages.  

[Microbiota](/Microbiota) ([communities](/Community_(ecology)) of [microorganisms](/Microorganism)) that reside on the [skin](/Skin), typically [human skin](/Human_skin).  

Many of them are [bacteria](/Bacterium) of which there are around 1,000 species upon human skin from nineteen [phyla](/Phylum). &#91;1&#93; &#91;2&#93; Most are found in the superficial layers of the [epidermis](/Epidermis_(skin)) and the upper parts of [hair follicles](/Hair_follicle).  

Skin flora is usually non‑pathogenic, and either [commensal](/Commensalism) (are not harmful to their host) or [mutualistic](/Mutualism_(biology)) (offer a benefit). The benefits bacteria can offer include preventing transient [pathogenic](/Pathogenic) organisms from [colonizing](/Infection) the skin surface, either by competing for nutrients, secreting chemicals against them, or stimulating the skin's [immune system](/Immune_system). &#91;3&#93; However, resident microbes can cause [skin diseases](/Skin_disease) and enter the [blood system](/Blood_system), creating life‑threatening diseases, particularly in [immunosuppressed](/Immunosuppressed) people. &#91;3&#93;  

A major non‑human skin flora is [Batrachochytrium dendrobatidis](/Batrachochytrium_dendrobatidis) , a [chytrid](/Chytrid) and non‑hyphal zoosporic fungus that causes [chytridiomycosis](/Chytridiomycosis), an infectious disease thought to be responsible for the [decline in amphibian populations](/Decline_in_amphibian_populations). &#91;4&#93;  

---  

## Species variety  

### Bacteria  

[Scanning electron microscope](/Scanning_electron_microscope) image of [Staphylococcus epidermidis](/Staphylococcus_epidermidis) , one of roughly a thousand [bacteria](/Bacteria) species present on [human skin](/Human_skin). Though usually not [pathogenic](/Pathogenic), it can cause [skin infections](/Skin_infection) and even life‑threatening illnesses in those that are [immunocompromised](/Immunocompromised).  

The estimate of the number of bacteria species present on skin has been radically changed by the use of [16S ribosomal RNA](/16S_ribosomal_RNA) to identify bacterial species present on skin samples direct from their genetic material. Previously such identification had depended upon [microbiological culture](/Microbiological_culture) upon which many varieties of bacteria did not grow and so were hidden to science. &#91;1&#93;  

[Staphylococcus epidermidis](/Staphylococcus_epidermidis) and [Staphylococcus aureus](/Staphylococcus_aureus) were thought from cultural based research to be dominant. However 16S ribosomal RNA research finds that while common, these species make up only 5 % of skin bacteria. However, skin variety provides a rich and diverse habitat for [bacteria](/Bacteria). Most come from four phyla: [Actinomycetota](/Actinomycetota) (51.8 %), [Bacillota](/Bacillota) (24.4 %), [Pseudomonadota](/Pseudomonadota) (16.5 %), and [Bacteroidota](/Bacteroidota) (6.3 %). &#91;5&#93;  

### Ecology of the 20 sites on the skin studied in the Human Microbiome Project  

There are three main ecological areas: sebaceous, moist, and dry. [Propionibacteria](/Propionibacteria) and [Staphylococci](/Staphylococci) species were the main species in [sebaceous](/Sebaceous) areas. In moist places on the body [Corynebacteria](/Corynebacteria) together with Staphylococci dominate. In dry areas, there is a mixture of species but [Betaproteobacteria](/Betaproteobacteria) and [Flavobacteriales](/Flavobacteriales) are dominant. Ecologically, sebaceous areas had greater species richness than moist and dry ones. The areas with least similarity between people in species were the spaces between [fingers](/Finger), the spaces between [toes](/Toe), [axillae](/Axillae), and [umbilical cord](/Umbilical_cord) stump. Most similarly were beside the [nostril](/Nostril), nares (inside the nostril), and on the back. &#91;1&#93;  

